SIMPLE: regenerate
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Regenerate
<hw>Re*gen"er*ate</hw> <pr>(-?t)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>regeneratus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>regenerare</ets> to regenerate;
pref. <ets>re-</ets> re- + <ets>generare</ets> to beget. See
<er>Generate</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Reproduced.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The earthly author of my blood,⟦br⟧
Whose youthful spirit, in me <qex>regenerate</qex>,⟦br⟧
Doth with a twofold vigor lift me up.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Theol.)</fld> <def>Born anew; become Christian;
renovated in heart; changed from a natural to a spiritual
state.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1210 --></p>

<p><ent>Regenerate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Regenerate
<hw>Re*gen"er*ate</hw> <pr>(r?*j?n"?r*?t)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To generate or produce anew; to reproduce; to give new
life, strength, or vigor to.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Through all the soil a genial fferment spreads.⟦br⟧
<qex>Regenerates</qex> the plauts, and new adorns the meads.</q>
<rj><qau>Blackmore.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Theol.)</fld> <def>To cause to be spiritually born
anew; to cause to become a Christian; to convert from sin to holiness;
to implant holy affections in the heart of.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Hence, to make a radical change for the better in
the character or condition of; <as>as, to <ex>regenerate</ex>
society</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Regenerateness</ent>⟦br⟧
